00:40:44.430 --> 00:40:48.380
that we were not a bar company
but a healthy snacking company,

00:40:48.380 --> 00:40:51.240
and a healthy eating company,
whose common thread was not

00:40:51.240 --> 00:40:55.146
the bar format, but the use of
nutritionally rich ingredients

00:40:55.146 --> 00:40:56.520
that you could
see and pronounce.

00:40:56.520 --> 00:40:59.574
So we were thinking about
doing another granola bar.

00:40:59.574 --> 00:41:01.115
And we thought, then
people are going

00:41:01.115 --> 00:41:02.614
to think we're the
KIND bar company.

00:41:02.614 --> 00:41:05.312
Even right now, they still--
not to put you on the spot.

00:41:05.312 --> 00:41:07.270
VISHAL JAIN: My apologies
to the clusters team.

00:41:07.270 --> 00:41:08.270
DANIEL LUBETZKY:
But a lot of people

00:41:08.270 --> 00:41:09.728
still think of us
as a bar company.

00:41:09.728 --> 00:41:13.930
And we early on decided
to do the clusters.

00:41:13.930 --> 00:41:15.300
It's a much smaller category.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.470
The bag granola category, I
think it's like $400 million

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:24.550
compared to the granola
bar category, which

00:41:24.550 --> 00:41:25.530
is like $4 billion.

00:41:25.530 --> 00:41:28.540
So granola bars are
a much bigger space.

00:41:28.540 --> 00:41:30.440
Logically, we should
have gone there.

00:41:30.440 --> 00:41:34.440
But we consciously decided
to first go to clusters

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:37.510
because we wanted to convey
to the consumer this point.

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:40.100
And when you're
building products,

00:41:40.100 --> 00:41:45.130
oftentimes the second line
you introduce is as or more

00:41:45.130 --> 00:41:47.220
important than the
first, because you're

00:41:47.220 --> 00:41:49.270
connecting the dots.

00:41:49.270 --> 00:41:52.536
Actually, Eric Berman, who
I think actually works here

00:41:52.536 --> 00:41:55.770
at Google, first
taught me that point.

00:41:58.860 --> 00:42:01.035
OK, this is what the KIND
Fruit + Nut Bars are.

00:42:01.035 --> 00:42:02.259
But what is a common thread?

00:42:02.259 --> 00:42:03.550
It could be that we use fruits.

00:42:03.550 --> 00:42:05.140
It could be that we use nuts.

00:42:05.140 --> 00:42:07.880
It could be that we use
nutritionally rich ingredients.

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:11.420
It could be the bar
format, so on and so forth.

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:14.230
By launching the
clusters, we connected,

00:42:14.230 --> 00:42:16.610
and we said, the common
thread is ingredients

00:42:16.610 --> 00:42:17.660
you can see an pronounce.

00:42:17.660 --> 00:42:20.530
It's nutritionally
rich ingredients.

00:42:20.530 --> 00:42:23.270
It's not necessarily
the bar format.

00:42:23.270 --> 00:42:26.400
We made a mistake when
we started with clusters

00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:30.160
several years ago in not
sufficiently understanding

00:42:30.160 --> 00:42:33.430
how sensitive those grains
that we were sourcing were.

00:42:33.430 --> 00:42:40.360
And the use of grains
that we use-- amaranth,

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:43.290
is very, very
susceptible to go rancid.

00:42:43.290 --> 00:42:45.760
And so you need to treat
it with a lot of respect.

00:42:45.760 --> 00:42:47.900
You really, really,
really need to protect it.

00:42:47.900 --> 00:42:50.800
And early on when we launched
the clusters, like a month

00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:53.610
into it, we started getting
complaints from consumers

00:42:53.610 --> 00:42:55.650
that they felt the
product was rancid.

00:42:55.650 --> 00:42:58.150
And we were freaking out,
because of the promise

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:00.300
that I told you that
I promised myself

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:01.980
I would make to our consumers.

00:43:01.980 --> 00:43:07.350
And we got on average for
a KIND bar product line--

00:43:07.350 --> 00:43:09.080
I'm doing it from
memory, so I may get it

00:43:09.080 --> 00:43:11.320
a little off-- but it's
something like less

00:43:11.320 --> 00:43:12.980
than one complaint per million.

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:15.130
It's I think 0.01
complaint per million.

00:43:15.130 --> 00:43:16.960
We almost don't get complaints.

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:20.220
All of a sudden we got
200 complaints per million

00:43:20.220 --> 00:43:21.100
on the clusters.

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:23.780
And for us that was a very,
very large and alarming thing.

00:43:23.780 --> 00:43:26.060
Maybe in another company
it would be acceptable.

00:43:26.060 --> 00:43:28.510
For us, we were really
obsessing about quality.

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:31.210
We didn't want to
disappoint consumers.

00:43:31.210 --> 00:43:34.194
Because every one person that
complains, at least that person

00:43:34.194 --> 00:43:36.610
you can talk to them, and you
can fix the issue with them,

00:43:36.610 --> 00:43:39.060
and you can even build a
relationship with that person.

00:43:39.060 --> 00:43:40.560
But for every person
that complains,

00:43:40.560 --> 00:43:42.980
there's another
1,000 or 10,000 that

00:43:42.980 --> 00:43:44.640
just stop buying your product.

00:43:44.640 --> 00:43:47.550
Those are the people
that I worry about.

00:43:47.550 --> 00:43:50.810
So we very quickly, we had
a couple people camp out,

00:43:50.810 --> 00:43:52.300
I remember.

00:43:52.300 --> 00:43:56.170
Several of our team members
went there for weeks on end

00:43:56.170 --> 00:43:57.410
to try to fix the issue.

00:43:57.410 --> 00:44:00.785
And I was really appreciative
of their major sacrifice

00:44:00.785 --> 00:44:02.820
on behalf of the
company to fix it.

00:44:02.820 --> 00:44:07.190
And within two, three months,
we improved our practices

00:44:07.190 --> 00:44:09.750
for sourcing these grains.

00:44:09.750 --> 00:44:11.710
Within a few months,
the number of complaints

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:14.060
was back down to like
0.01 per million,

00:44:14.060 --> 00:44:15.730
or whatever is in the book.

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:22.250
But it was a humbling lesson in,
when you're entering adjacency,

00:44:22.250 --> 00:44:27.839
be careful about sourcing
ingredients with care.

